<div class="uk-grid tm-leading-article"><div class="uk-width-1-1"><article class="uk-article tm-article" data-permalink="http://intuuchina.com/en/china-info/95-el-principio-del-mei-guan-xi">


	


		<h1 class="uk-article-title">
					<a href="/en/china-info/95-el-principio-del-mei-guan-xi" title="El principio del “mei guan xi”">El principio del “mei guan xi”</a>
			</h1>
	
	

		<p class="uk-article-meta">

		Written on <time datetime="2016-07-25">25 July 2016</time>.
	</p>
	

	
		<div>
		<p><span style="font-family: Calibri;">La segunda vez que vengo y nada ha cambiado desde la &uacute;ltima vez que pis&eacute; China. A pesar de haber tenido ya casi un a&ntilde;o de experiencia en este pa&iacute;s, sigue sorprendi&eacute;ndome en todas sus manifestaciones.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Calibri;">Gracias a mi primer contacto, exactamente el a&ntilde;o pasado, he empezado a pregonar por todo el mundo, lo que yo llamo, el principio del &ldquo;mei guan xi&rdquo;. Desconozco si tal principio realmente existe en la filosof&iacute;a china o en cualquier otra filosof&iacute;a existente.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Calibri;">&iquest;Qu&eacute; quiere decir? Hay muchas traducciones que se pueden encontrar en la red. El concepto de &ldquo;mei guan xi&rdquo; se traduce como: &ldquo;No pasa nada, It doesn't matter, It's all right, Sin problemas...&rdquo; Y, os preguntar&eacute;is a qu&eacute; me ha llevado a desarrollar este principio para mi d&iacute;a a d&iacute;a, aplicable tanto en China como en otro pa&iacute;s del mundo.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Calibri;">Mi historia comienza nada m&aacute;s llegar. Esta vez, la primera semana china me hab&iacute;a recibido ya con muchos &ldquo;problemas t&eacute;cnicos&rdquo; en casa. Desde un retrete bloqueado, una lavadora que intenta despegar, un internet que tiene wifi pero no conecta a la red, hasta una e-bike que parece arrollada por un cami&oacute;n. &iexcl;Y todo esto en menos de un mes!</span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Calibri;">Si todo esto me hubiera pasado en Espa&ntilde;a, por ejemplo, sin titubear ya estar&iacute;a llamando a Atenci&oacute;n al Cliente a reclamar. Pero en este pa&iacute;s, si una persona no est&aacute; acostumbrada a los &ldquo;est&aacute;ndares chinos&rdquo; ni tampoco domina el lenguaje de Confucio, con estos peque&ntilde;os problemas t&eacute;cnicos, a cualquiera se le hubiera agotado la paciencia. Ya no s&oacute;lo por la barrera idiom&aacute;tica, sino tambi&eacute;n por la lentitud de los chinos (cuando quieren) para hacer las cosas.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Calibri;">Mi chino b&aacute;sico de supervivencia me ayud&oacute; un poco a expresar cu&aacute;l era mi problema, pero el m&eacute;rito se lo lleva IntuuChina ya que uno de sus servicios es proporcionar a una persona que se encarga de este tipo de cosas. La sensaci&oacute;n de poder contar con alguien casi a cualquier hora del d&iacute;a para&nbsp; cualquier &ldquo;problema t&eacute;cnico&rdquo;, tanto en casa como con los papeleos, y que se encargue de gestionarlo todo sin tener que andar detr&aacute;s de nadie, supone un gran alivio.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span>El hecho de tener a esta persona disponible para este tipo de cuestiones, que te entiende y sabe c&oacute;mo comunic&aacute;rselo al local chino, es un gran apoyo para poder </span><span>sobre</span><span>llevar el d&iacute;a a d&iacute;a en este pa&iacute;s. En el caso de no tenerlo, recomiendo que vayan practicando la &ldquo;filosof&iacute;a del mei guan xi&rdquo; de forma intensiva ya que si no trabajan la paciencia en este pa&iacute;s, terminar&aacute;n por perder los estribos y seguro que no conseguir&aacute;n gran cosa.</span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Calibri;">This is the second time I&rsquo;ve lived in China and nothing has changed since the last time I set foot here. Though last time it was in a small city called Yiwu (Zhejiang Province), this time my destination was <span style="background: yellow;">Shanghai.</span> Despite having had almost a year of experience in this country, it continues to amaze me in <span style="background: yellow;">all its manifestations</span>.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Calibri;">Thanks to my first experience in China last year, I started to preach all around the world what I call the principle of<strong> "mei guan xi".</strong> So what does it mean? I&rsquo;m not sure if such a principle already exists in Chinese philosophy but there are many translations you can find online with just a simple Google search. The concept of <strong>&ldquo;mei guan xi&rdquo;</strong> can be translated as, &ldquo;no big deal, it doesn&rsquo;t matter, it&rsquo;s alright, or no problem&rdquo;. You may ask what has led me to develop this principle to my day to day life here that&rsquo;s applicable in China and everywhere else in the world for that matter. </span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Calibri;">My story begins as soon as I arrived to my apartment. My first week in China brought lots of obstacles due to "technical problems" at home. From a blocked toilet, a washing machine that tries to take flight, having wifi that doesn&rsquo;t connect to the network, to an e-bike that looks like it was hit by a truck. All of this happened in less than a month&rsquo;s time, one right after the other!</span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span>If </span><span>all of this </span><span>would have happened in Spain</span><span> I would be calling customer service to complain </span><span>without hesitation</span><span>.</span><span>I</span><span>n this country if a person is not used to the "Chinese standard" nor dominates the language of Confucius </span><span>they are going to be stressing. N</span><span>ot only </span><span>is there a</span><span> language barrier, but</span><span> a cultural difference where customer service can be slow. </span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span>My <span style="background: yellow;">basic Chinese</span> along with my innovative survival skills (i.e. signing overtly and taking a picture of the toilet) helped me explain some of my problems.</span><span>T</span><span>he </span><span>outstanding </span><span>merit </span><span>really goes to </span><span style="font-family: Calibri; background: yellow;">IntuuChin</span><span style="font-family: Calibri; background: yellow;">a</span><span>, where they take charge of <span style="background: yellow;">assisting interns</span> with their needs and any issues that come about</span><span>. </span><span>They have a Chinese assistant who helps you overcome communication barriers. </span><span>The feeling </span><span>of having</span><span> someone </span><span>available for help at </span><span>any time of </span><span>the </span><span>day</span><span>,</span><span> for any </span><span>problem, is a life-saver. They save me from stress </span><span>both at home and with </span><span>all </span><span>the paperwork</span><span>.</span><span>They</span><span> manage to take care of everything without having to go after anyone,</span><span> and</span><span> i</span><span>t&rsquo;</span><span>s a huge relief</span><span>. </span></span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Calibri;">The fact that you can have these resources to adapt to your new life in China is a great support that can help you cope with day to day obstacles you may have. If you don&rsquo;t have this kind of support system, then I highly recommend you practice my <strong>&ldquo;mei guan xi</strong>&rdquo; philosophy intensively or else you will eventually lose your temper and you won&rsquo;t achieve anything. </span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Calibri;">&ldquo;Mei Guan Xi&rdquo; translated as &ldquo;no big deal, it&rsquo;s alright, or no problem&rdquo; is a mantra one can practice to remain calm when things go wrong China.</span></p>	</div>
	
	
	
	




</article>
</div></div><div class="uk-grid" data-uk-grid-match data-uk-grid-margin><div class="uk-width-medium-1-2"><article class="uk-article tm-article" data-permalink="http://intuuchina.com/en/china-info/94-about-intuuchina">


	


		<h1 class="uk-article-title">
					<a href="/en/china-info/94-about-intuuchina" title="About Intuuchina">About Intuuchina</a>
			</h1>
	
	

		<p class="uk-article-meta">

		Written on <time datetime="2016-07-25">25 July 2016</time>.
	</p>
	

	
		<div>
		<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">Hooray! Don&rsquo;t judge us too much if we congratulate ourselves&hellip;</span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">We&rsquo;ve been featured in B-UIC Magazine published by the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences (FCES) at the Universitat Internacional de Catalunya (UIC) in Barcelona, Spain.&nbsp; As our founders all hail from Barcelona, and Marc Ramon Hernadez graduated from the esteemed UIC, we are flattered by the attention and honored to be a window into Chinese business. </span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">In the article Hernandez and Fernando de Zavala, two of three founders, are interviewed about their work experience in China and their motivation to start <strong><span style="color: red;">Intuu</span>China</strong>.&nbsp; Hernandez and de Zavala explain that <strong><span style="color: red;">Intuu</span>China</strong>, which offers post-arrival support, personalized placement and business mentors, serves a niche in the China recruiting market: &ldquo;We immediately realized that these [other headhunting companies] were selling their practices as an isolated service and they were placing you in companies that were not really your objective&hellip;we realized that if the two market leaders were providing a service that was below expectations, then there was a need there, a gap to be filled.&rdquo; </span></p>
<p style="margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: 0cm; margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">Throughout the post, Hernandez and de Zavala mention their own personal experiences studying and working in China, careful to point out differences with other parts of the world. A key point is the intensity of business relationship.&nbsp; Unlike the West, which relies on business networking as a pool of skills, business contacts are much more familial in China.&nbsp; </span></p>
<p style="margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: 0cm; margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">Hernandez explains the need for &lsquo;guanxi&rsquo; the unique word to describe the Chinese corporate kin-like relationship.&nbsp; He remembers the difficulty of beginning a career in China without having his own &lsquo;guanxi&rsquo;: the main drawback [to working in China] is that it is very difficult to establish commercial relationships and not to be passed over if you don&rsquo;t have a good position, work in a good company or have not obtained a first introduction through someone trusted by the person you want to be introduced to.&rdquo;&nbsp; </span></p>
<p style="margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: 0cm; margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">We&rsquo;re so proud of Marc and pleased with the story because it showcases our team&rsquo;s knowledge of working in China.&nbsp; Additionally, the piece illustrates our eagerness to connect students and young professionals to this part of the world so that they can experience dynamic market for themselves.&nbsp; </span></p>
<p style="margin-top: 0cm; margin-right: 0cm; margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">Please find a link to the entire magazine and full version of the story appearing on pages 27-28 via this link: </span><a href="http://www.uic.es/en/b-uic"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria; color: #103cc0;">http://www.uic.es/en/b-uic</span></a></span></p>	</div>
	
	
	
	




</article>
<article class="uk-article tm-article" data-permalink="http://intuuchina.com/en/china-info/93-job-interviews">


	


		<h1 class="uk-article-title">
					<a href="/en/china-info/93-job-interviews" title="Job Interviews Tips">Job Interviews Tips</a>
			</h1>
	
	

		<p class="uk-article-meta">

		Written on <time datetime="2016-07-22">22 July 2016</time>.
	</p>
	

	
		<div>
		<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">Interviews are a play of strategy. Employer and potential-hire rally questions and answers trying to best the other with the element of surprise. It&rsquo;s the interviewer designing the question to test the interviewee&rsquo;s spontaneous critical thinking and personality under stress.&nbsp; It&rsquo;s the interviewee practicing the most creative answer of where he or she will be in 10 years.&nbsp; But at the end of the day, it comes down to more than what either party says, it&rsquo;s the flow of the conversation. </span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">In a candid style, Jeff Harden of Inc. Magazine outlines &lsquo;9 Things Every Interviewer Wishes You Knew&rsquo; </span></p>
<ol>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">I want you to be likeable. </span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">I don&rsquo;t want you to immediately say you want the job.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">I want you to stand out&hellip;</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">&hellip;but not for being negative.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">I want you to ask a lot of questions about what really matters to you&hellip;</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">&hellip;but only if the majority of those questions relate to real work.</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">I love when you bring a &lsquo;project.&rsquo;</span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">At the end I want you to ask for the job&hellip;and I want to know why. </span></li>
<li><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">I want you to follow up&hellip;especially if it&rsquo;s genuine. </span></li>
</ol>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">Sounds intense&hellip;but don&rsquo;t let it scare you. Our job at <strong><span style="color: red;">Intuu</span>China</strong> is to interview clients for the purpose of getting them interviews, so we&rsquo;re quite used to this beast.&nbsp; </span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">We really enjoyed his piece and wanted to share it with you (find the full text here </span><a href="http://linkd.in/1lmZKVC"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">http://linkd.in/1lmZKVC</span></a><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">).&nbsp; Two things that resonated most with us was the need to have made the job application personal and difference between being the &lsquo;impressive&rsquo; and the &lsquo;polite&rsquo; candidate.</span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">For the first, Harden repeats that applicants should be knowledgeable of the company to the extent that they could ask specific questions about the role and company.&nbsp; He specifies that these questions are not about benefits or hours but rather, company goals, manager expectations and how you will be evaluated.&nbsp; Additionally, he says the best candidates will be able to suggest a new company project that utilizes their past work skills. Also, he notes that interviewees should not immediately state that they want the job&mdash;he says eagerness can be mistaken for flippancy.&nbsp; Hardin suggests asserting your desire for the job at the end of the interview and in the follow-up</span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-size: 12pt; font-family: Cambria;">Second, Harden details that candidates who have unique personalities will come to be known by those traits during the interview process.&nbsp; He says that an interviewee&rsquo;s impression lasts longer than a CV and candidates should be personable.&nbsp; Additionally, the post-interview follow-up is also critically important but the generic &lsquo;Please advise if you need more information&rsquo; message is not going to cut it.&nbsp; Referencing conversation points from the interview shows your engagement in the process and commitment ability.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>	</div>
	
	
	
	




</article>
</div><div class="uk-width-medium-1-2"><article class="uk-article tm-article" data-permalink="http://intuuchina.com/en/china-info/92-new-year">


	


		<h1 class="uk-article-title">
					<a href="/en/china-info/92-new-year" title="New Year">New Year</a>
			</h1>
	
	

		<p class="uk-article-meta">

		Written on <time datetime="2016-07-22">22 July 2016</time>.
	</p>
	

	
		<div>
		<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Cambria; font-size: 12pt;">It&rsquo;s always seemed a little peculiar that the letting go of 365 days and buckling down into new resolutions only required the strike of Midnight.&nbsp; With blasts of fireworks and pops of champagne, the Western hemisphere progresses through the solar calendar in as much time as the peck of a New Years Kiss. </span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Cambria; font-size: 12pt;">Ringing in the Lunar New Year, however, is quite a bit more dramatic.&nbsp; Over the course of 15 days, China goes into holiday mode: a majority of stores, restaurants and offices close, families travel together, and fireworks are lit all day long.&nbsp; The new icon of the year, the Horse for 2014, becomes the most popular cartoon, adorning everything from red envelopes stuffed with money (hongbao) to special edition baijiu containers.&nbsp; Train stations, airports and highways experience record traffic as 3.62 billion passenger trips happened throughout China this year. </span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Cambria; font-size: 12pt;">Concealing the holiday cheer this year, however, was a thick layer of concern about smog.&nbsp; It is no secret that China&rsquo;s air quality has worsened, or at least become a bigger worry, in recent months.&nbsp; With Shanghai and Beijing consistently posting AQI (air quality index) numbers above the healthy limits, government officials and environmental organizations encouraged people to cut back on the pyrotechnics.&nbsp; In fact, the LATimes.com reported that there was general support behind the extinguishment, with 81% of Shanghai respondents saying they supported a total ban.&nbsp; Exact figures on the number of booms aren&rsquo;t expected but we can say for certain that it&rsquo;s a Happy New Year. </span></p>
<p style="text-align: justify;"><span style="font-family: Cambria; font-size: 12pt;">Sending wishes for the best Year of the Horse from us at IntuuChina!! </span></p>	</div>
	
	
	
	




</article>
<article class="uk-article tm-article" data-permalink="http://intuuchina.com/en/china-info/90-golden-week-china">


	


		<h1 class="uk-article-title">
					<a href="/en/china-info/90-golden-week-china" title="Golden Week China">Golden Week China</a>
			</h1>
	
	

		<p class="uk-article-meta">

		Written on <time datetime="2016-07-22">22 July 2016</time>.
	</p>
	

	
		<div>
		<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;">Mid-Autumn Festival earlier this September has left everyone stuffed with mooncakes. For those not currently in China, it is around this time when people are bombarded with pictures, news articles and adverts of scrumptious mooncake. This public holiday involves family gatherings and outdoor activities such as floating sky lanterns and giving offerings to the full moon. Before heading home for the holidays people at the office normally give each other a smooth, melt-in-your-mouth pastry layer enfolding a sweet, dense filling that may sometimes contain a salted egg yolk in their center (the symbol of the full moon).</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;"></span><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;">Just as we reminisce of this public holiday though, October starts with a national week-long holiday known as Golden Week. Golden Week in China normally falls on the first of October where millions of Chinese travel domestically for family reunions, vacations or shopping malls. Alternatively (and probably wisely) some go abroad as this week is when everyone recommends you to avoid travel at all costs.</span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;">Claustrophobics prepare yourselves: see here and here. Golden Week was originally set in place to allow workers to make long-distance trips to visit family which would in turn expand the domestic tourism market. Whether it&rsquo;s a good thing for the economy or not, it at least means you&rsquo;ll be out of the office for a week and that&rsquo;s something everyone can look forward to. In any case, for those unlucky (or lucky) ones that will stay put during this National Week in China can enjoy your Golden Week in China by relaxing in bed. Watch a marathon rerun of all your favorite sitcoms or films, thankful that you&rsquo;re not queuing for hours on end. If you&rsquo;re still disappointed at the lack of sightseeing you&rsquo;ll actually be doing this week in China, experience virtual China from the comfort of your bed! https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KCRZcg665zM Golden Week in China is upon us and for those of you thinking of traveling around China, think again. Enjoy your week long holidays in Shanghai. </span></p>
<p><span style="font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12pt;">Enjoy national holidays in China by going abroad, outside of China, or staying put as Golden Week in China is one of the worst weeks to travel.</span></p>
<p><img src="images/2CF8507D00000578-3256140-image-a-42_1443715950439.jpg" alt="2CF8507D00000578-3256140-image-a-42_1443715950439.jpg" /></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>	</div>
	
	
	
	




</article>
